The number of binding sites n were evaluated from the plots of Log ((F 0 − F)/F −
F ∞
) against log [Q] (not shown) for the respective interactions between GQDs and the ZnPcs (Table 2). The results indicated that multiple interactions existed between the GQDs and the respective ZnPcs. Worthy of note is the interaction and higher values of n and Kb for GQDs and cationic ZnTmPyPc. This can be judged from the perspective that both ionic and π–π interactions are at play for ZnTmPyPc interaction with GQDs. Strong ionic interaction between oppositely charged Pcs and carbon nanomaterials of fullerenes and graphene have been reported upon simple mixing of the molecules [41]. This observation is also consistent with our study. Additionally, the cationic ZnTmPyPc used in this study has pyridyloxy (Scheme 2) substituent with an extended π electron system which affords more π–π interaction compared to the ZnTAPc (Scheme 1) bearing no extended π electron substituents. Also, compared to the ZnTCPPc with extended π electron(s) from the phenoxy ring, the ionic interaction favors more binding interaction of cationic ZnTmPyPc with GQDs, hence the observed higher binding constants (Table 2).
